frameDefinitions: An Entity is evaluated for whether or not it belongs to a particular Reference_category in a context where its category membership is doubtful.
A person, the Cognizer, thinks about a Topic over a period of time.
This frame concerns a specific subset of Instances of a Type which are evaluated in terms of their similarity to a conceptual prototype of the Type.
This frame contains adjectives and nouns that describe the truth or sincerity of communication.

Against the background of a contextually salient non-real world, for instance a hypothetical, imagined, simulated, expected, projected, or dream world, an Instance of a Type encountered in a relation or event in the real world is presented as being different from the instance found in the non-real world.
A particular piece of Information is evaluated for its accuracy.
frameExamples:
It can be hard to get your money back after discovering you've bought a <t>bogus</t>
autograph for hundreds or thousands of dollars!
The men were silently <t>mulling</t> <t>over</t> the proposition of committing an assassination
Evelyn was <t>candid</t> with me about the party.
Is your reputation at risk due to <t>incorrect</t> information?
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Entity</fen> that is being evaluated in terms of whether it is an instance of the <fen>Reference_category</fen>.
The type relative to which the <fen>Entity</fen> is evaluated.
With a target verb, the Cognizer is usually expressed as an External Argument, with the Topic appearing as an Object NP, a gerundive verbal Complement, or a PP.
With a target verb, the <fen>Topic</fen> is usually expressed as an Object NP, a gerundive verbal complement, or a PP.
The time at which the <fen>Cognizer</fen> considers the <fen>Topic</fen>.
A thing or episode that is considered exemplary of a certain <fen>Type</fen>.
The category of things or events from which an <fen>Instance</fen> is picked out.

The <fen>Speaker</fen> produces the <fen>Message</fen>, the truth or sincerity of which is at issue. It is normally expressed as the External Argument of predicative uses of the <t>target</t> word, or as the Nominal Head of prenominal uses.

<fen>Message</fen> is the communicative content whose truth or sincerity is at issue. This role does not normally co-occur with the other FEs in this frame. When it does occur, it is normally the External Argument of a predicative use of the <t>Target</t> word, or the modified Nominal Head in a prenominal use.

The <fen>Topic</fen> is the subject matter to which the <fen>Message</fen> pertains. It often occurs without the <fen>Message</fen> role in predicative uses of the <t>target</t> word. It is normally expressed as a PP Complement headed by 'about'.
<fen>Medium</fen> is the physical or abstract setting in which the <fen>Message</fen> is conveyed.
The real-world individual--a concrete or abstract thing or an event--which differs from its counterpart in a discourse-salient non-real world.
A kind of entity, instances of which are expected to occur in both the real and the non-real world.
The <fen>Information</fen> matches or does not match the facts of the world.
The <fen>Source</fen> is the agent who holds the correct/incorrect information.
The Topic about which the Source has accurate information.
The <fen>Time</fen> at which the <fen>Information</fen> or the <fen>Source</fen> is correct.
listRoleExamples: <fex>The bomb found at the US Embassy in Berlin</fex> was fake.
Evelyn made some candid remarks <fex>in French</fex>.
In May of 1994, FBI agents working for Mr. Fiske interviewed Mrs. Foster, showed her <fex>an ACTUAL  gun</fex>, not a photo, and asked her if she could identify the gun.
